Introduction to Events:
----------------------
Events are signals that something happened â€” user interaction or browser action.

<button onclick="alert('Clicked!')">Click me</button>
Events are fired when users interact (click, type, scroll, etc.).

Can listen using:
HTML attribute - onclick="..."
DOM property - elem.onclick = handler
addEventListener() - modern & preferred

Introduction to Browser Events:
------------------------------
Each event type (click, input, load, keydown, etc.) has an event object with details.

button.addEventListener("click", function(event) {
  alert(event.type);   // click
  alert(event.target); // element clicked
});

Common event types:

Mouse: click, dblclick, mousemove, mouseover, mousedown
Keyboard: keydown, keyup
Form: input, submit, change, focus
Document: DOMContentLoaded, load
Window: resize, scroll

Event Bubbling and Capturing:
----------------------------
When an event happens on an element, it travels:

Capturing phase - from root to target
Bubbling phase - from target back to root

elem.addEventListener("click", handler, true); // capture phase
elem.addEventListener("click", handler, false); // bubble phase (default)

Event Delegation:
-----------------
Attach one event listener on a parent instead of many on children.
Why useful:
Handles future dynamically-added elements.
Saves memory (only one listener).
Uses event bubbling.

Browser Default Actions:
-----------------------
Some events have default browser behavior (e.g., links navigate, forms submit).
